solutions.content:
Modern declarative JavaScript use of string destructuring and array methods.

Please keep in mind, this is an example of declarative JavaScript programming vs imperative solutions.
The solution won't be the fastest or the most memory efficient.

Here's some references if you're more interested about what reduce and map can do:
https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/reduce
https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/map

```
var shortestToChar = function(S, C) {

    // We create an array of indices of where the character C occurs
    //
    // [...S] is a string destructuring, we turn the string into an array
    // of characters (in JavaScript, it's really just single character strings)
    //
    // On this new string array, we use Array.reduce(), which is a powerful way of
    // exploring arrays with a callback function. The callback function in this example is
    // (acc, currC, ind) => currC === C ? [...acc, ind] : acc
    // which is stating "for each element, take the 'Accumulator', 'Current Element', and 'Index'
    // and return what our next accumulator will be". The accumulator was initialized to be
    // an empty array and if the character matches, we copy our current accumulator array into
    // a new array and append the current Index. If it doesn't match, just return our Accumulator
    //
    // The ultimate result is our accumulator, which is an array of indices.

    const indexesOfC = [...S].reduce(
        (acc, currC, currInd) => currC === C ? [...acc, currInd] : acc
        , [])

    // Here, we are mapping each character to a number. This is the perfect time
    // to use Array.map()! Array.map also uses a callback function, but this time it's
    // (char, ind) => <some code returning what we want to map>
    // "char" being "Current Element" and "ind" being an optional parameter "Current Index"
    //
    // We then run an Array.reduce() on our indices of character C. This time the accumulator
    // is going to be recording the shortest distance from the current S index to the closest
    // C index. We return the smaller of the saved value (acc) and the distance (Math.abs(ind - curr))
    //
    // Note that the accumulator is initially set to Infinity. You can also use Number.MAX_VALUE.

    return [...S].map((char, ind) => 
        indexesOfC.reduce((acc, curr) => 
            Math.min(acc, Math.abs(ind - curr))
        , Infinity)
    )
};
```

