The 1st pattern that came to mind was to use a **Sliding Window**. We can do it T:O(n), S:O(n) like the accepted solution. The below Java code runs in 1ms. It uses 2 pointers to check for the closest occurence of C from i and the second closest occurence of C (if it exists) from i. Here, we also get the *Mininimum Absolute Distance* between *(curr - i)* and *(next - i)*. As soon as i is closer to next that it is to curr, we update curr with next and next with the next occurene of C (if it exists) in the list of occurences we created earlier.

**Algo:**

1.  Store all occurences of C in S into a list
2.  Go through S once by checking for Min_Absolute_Distance(curr - i, next - i)
3.  Update curr and next accordingly as soon as i is closer to next than curr

```java
class Solution {
    public int[] shortestToChar(String S, char C) {
        int[] output = new int[S.length()];

        // Handle edge cases (0, null, etc)
        if (S == null || S.length() == 0)
            return output;

        // Store all positions of C in S
        List<Integer> occurrences = new ArrayList<>();
        for (int i=0; i<S.length(); i++)
            if (S.charAt(i) == C) 
                occurrences.add(i);

        // Sliding window  
        int j = 0;
        int curr = occurrences.get(j);
        int next = occurrences.size() > 1 ? occurrences.get(++j) : curr;
        for (int i=0; i<S.length(); i++) {                        
            if (Math.abs(curr-i) < Math.abs(next-i))
                output[i] = Math.abs(curr-i);
            else {
                output[i] = Math.abs(next-i);
                curr = next;
                if (j+1 < occurrences.size())              
                    next = occurrences.get(++j);
                else
                    next = curr;
            }                                            
        }   

        return output;
    }     
}
```
