Here's the solution:

```
class Solution {
    public String reverseParentheses(String s) {
        int l = s.length();
        /* If length is 0 means there is no character so empty string is returned
           if length is 1 means there is no parentheses(since parentheses are balanced) so the string is returned*/
        if(l==0||l==1){return s;}

        /* If length is 2 either there will be 2 parentheses or 2 characters */
        if(l==2){
            if(s.charAt(0)=='('){return "";}
            return s;
        }

        String subs;

        /* StringBuilder is used since string is immutable*/
        StringBuilder str = new StringBuilder(s), substr;

        /* This stack is used to store the indices of opening brackets */
        Stack<Integer> st = new Stack<>();
        int x;
        Character ch;

        /* Idea here is quite simple: 
        - Find the matching closing bracket (by help of stack)
        - Get index of opening bracket (from stack)
          and index of closing bracket (from str)
        - Replace the substring from opening bracket index to closing bracket index(both inclusive) by the reverse of substring from opening bracket index + 1 to closing bracket index-1(both inclusive) 
        - Repeat above process for every pair of matching parantheses
        */

        for(int i=0;i<str.length();i++){
            ch = str.charAt(i);
            if(ch=='('){
                st.push(i);
            }
            else if(ch==')'){
                x = st.pop();
                subs = str.substring(x+1,i);
                substr = new StringBuilder(subs);
                str.replace(x,i+1, substr.reverse().toString());
                i-=2;
            }
        }

        return str.toString();
    }
}
```

