solutions.content:
The order of reversal doesnt matter. So we first reverse the inner most bracket and then the outer ones. Brute force would be to find the inner brackets first and then the outer ones and so on. Better approach will be to use stack. 
Whenever we encounter an opening bracket, we push the current string to stack. We will use this string when the inner brackets are reversed. 
Closing bracket means the current string needs to be reversed. So just reverse it and append the older string from stack's top to front of it. Dry the process on the given examples to understand better. Comment for any doubt.
```
class Solution {
public:
    string reverseParentheses(string s) {
        stack <string> st;
        string curr="";
        int n=s.size();
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
        {
            if(s[i]=='(')
            {
                st.push(curr);
                curr="";
                continue;
            }
            if(s[i]==')')
            {
                reverse(curr.begin(),curr.end());
                curr= st.top()+curr;
                st.pop();
                continue;
            }
            curr+=s[i];
        }
        return curr;
    }
};
```

