solutions.content:
**Approach :** 
Since the string is balanced , we can use stack to keep a record of encountered ```open and close brackets``` and reverse the substring in between ```each corresponding pair of open - close bracket.```
We keep pushing ```index of open brackets``` in the stack till we face our first ```close``` bracket.
As soon as we find our first ```close``` bracket , this means we can reverse substring between ```this close bracket and its corresponding open bracket``` (the index of this corresponding open bracket is the top of the stack).
Also , alongside this , we keep changing all the brackets ( open and closed both ) to any single common character so that at the end we can simply erase this common character from the whole string.

**STL :**
--> ```reverse(s.begin()+st.top()+1,s.begin()+i); // to reverse the substring between a pair of open and close bracket```
--> ```s.erase(remove(s.begin(),s.end(),'*'),s.end()); // to erase every '*' from the string```

**CODE :**
```
class Solution {
public:
    string reverseParentheses(string s) {
        int n = s.length();
        stack<int> st;
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            if(s[i]=='(')
                st.push(i);
            else if(s[i]==')'){
                reverse(s.begin()+st.top()+1,s.begin()+i);
                s[st.top()] = '*';
                s[i] = '*';
                st.pop();
            }
        }
        s.erase(remove(s.begin(),s.end(),'*'),s.end());
        return s;
    }
};
```

