# Intuition: Greedily take the maximum possible frequency for each character

# Approach: If a characters frequency is used, decrement it to the closest unused frequency

**1. Count Frequencys for each character**
- This is essential as the whole question is based around the frequencys opf characters
- we will store these in a hashmap of <char, int> pairs
- a slight optimization is to use a vector of size 26 to represent every charcater, however for simplicity this soloution utilises a hashmap
```
unordered_map<char,int> hmap;
for(char c : s) hmap[c]++;
```

Lets step through an example of this process
```
s = "aaabbbcc"

hashmap:
    a : 3
    b : 3
    c : 2
```

**2. Iterate through our hashmap and see if this freuency has been used or we need to make deletions**
- This is done in a some what greedy approach. If a characters frequency is unused, it takes it straight away. Otherwie we decrement its count by 1 untill it reaches an unused frequency or it becomes 0. We keep track of the deletions we do
- We will use another hashmap, this time a set to keep track of the used frequencys. A set is used as it has O(1) lookup time to see if a frequency has been used, aswell as O(1) insertion when we use a new frequency
```
 // iterate through hmap
for(auto& [c, freq] : hmap) {

    // decrement untill we find a unused frequency or it becomes -
    while(used.count(freq) && freq > 0) {
        count++; // increment deletions
        freq--; // decrement frequency of this character since we are removing one
    }
    // insert this valid frequency
        if(freq > 0)used.insert(freq);
}
```

- lets continue our example to illustrate this process
```
hashmap = a : 3, b : 3, c : 2
used = 

FIRST ITERATION
    character = a
    freq = 3
    3 has not been used so we add it to our set

SECOND ITERATION
used = 3

    character = b
    freq = 3

    3 has been used so we decrement it
    freq = 2                        decrements = 1

    2 has not been used so we place it in the used set

THIRD ITERATION
used = 3, 2

    character = c
    freq = 2

    2 has been used so we decrement it
    freq = 1                        decrements = 2

    1 has not been used so we add it to our used set

FINAL:
decrements = 2
used = 3 , 2 , 1

```

after this process we can return the number of decrements we had to make

# Complexity
**Time complexity: O(n)**  
- we iterate through input string of size n = O(n)
- iterating through hashmap is O(26) in the worst case when every character is a unique lower case = O(26) = O(1)
- Set lookups and insertions are O(1)

**Space complexity: O(1)**
- we always use a hashmap which in the worst case contains 26 characters (every lower case letter) = O(26) = O(1)
- The set will never exceed size 26 since if we only have 26 characters it is impossible to have more then 26 unique frequencys = O(26) = O(1)


# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int minDeletions(string s) {
        // store frequencys of every character
        unordered_map<char,int> hmap;
        for(char c : s) hmap[c]++;

        // used frequencys set
        unordered_set<int> used;

        int deletions = 0;  // counter of how many deletions we need to do

        // iterate through hmap
        for(auto& [c, freq] : hmap) {

            // decrement untill we find a unused frequency or it becomes -
            while(used.count(freq) && freq > 0) {
                deletions++; // increment deletions
                freq--; // decrement frequency of this character since we are removing one
            }
            // insert this valid frequency
            if(freq > 0)used.insert(freq);
        }

        return deletions;
    }
};
```

