# Intuition
We should first store the count of all the characters in a data structure. And then traverse it after sorting it.

# Approach
We will initialize a vector of pair of size 27 (26 alphabets and 1 extra space to handle heap overflow).
After this, we will store the count of each alphabet in vec.first and corresponding number (ex - 0 for 'a', 3 for 'd') in vec.second.
Now, sort the vector of pair in non-increasing order.
After this, we will traverse the vector of pair and if we find any frequency matching with its next element then we will decrease the current element by 1 and increase the answer by 1 and then again sort the vector of pair.
The base case to break out of loop would be, if frequency of current element is 1, In this case we will manually traverse the remaining elements and count until 0 is reached.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int minDeletions(string s) {
        int ans = 0,count = 0;
        vector<pair<int,int>> arr(27);
        for(int i=0;i<s.size();i++){ // storing count with alphabets in a vector of pair
            arr[int(s[i]-'a')].second = int(s[i]-'a');
            (arr[int(s[i]-'a')].first)++;
        }
        sort(arr.begin(),arr.end(),greater<pair<int, int> >()); // sorting in non-increasing order
        for(int i=0;i<arr.size()-1;i++){
            if(arr[i].first == arr[i+1].first){//if current frequency == 1, then traverse remaining elements and count number of 1s and break out of loop 
                if(arr[i].first == 1){
                    while(arr[i].first != 0){
                        count++;
                        i++;
                    }
                    ans += count -1;
                    break;
                }
                if(arr[i+1].first == 0 && arr[i+1].second == 0){//if next pair is (0,0) then simply break out of loop
                    break;
                }
                ans++;  
                (arr[i].first)--; //decrement current frequency by 1
                sort(arr.begin(),arr.end(),greater<pair<int, int> >())// sort again as changes are made in frequencies
                i=-1; // To start from i=0 again
            }
        } 
        return ans;
    }
};
```

