solutions.content:
Using a dictionary to track frequencies, iterate over the input string and determine how many times each character occurs.

Next, we sort by frequency descending. If the current frequency has not been used, then use it without deleting any characters. Otherwise, we need to delete some characters. The number to delete is determined by the last frequency we used, we must use 1 less.

The edge case here is, we can never delete more characters than occur in the input. If the last used frequency is 0, that is lowest freqency we can have.

```
public int MinDeletions(string s) {
    var counts = new Dictionary<char, int>();
    foreach (char c in s) {
        counts[c] = counts.GetValueOrDefault(c) + 1;
    }
    int last = int.MaxValue, deletions = 0;
    foreach (var p in counts.OrderByDescending(x => x.Value)) {
        last = Math.Min(last - 1, p.Value);
        last = Math.Max(last, 0);
        deletions += p.Value - last;
    }
    return deletions;
}
```

 - Runtime: O(N + K log K)
 - Space: O(K)

